In this update:
[1] Nigeria
[2] Global update as of 16 Nov 2011

******
[1] Nigeria
Date: Mon 21 Nov 2011
Source: BBC News Africa [edited]
http://www.bbc.co.uk/news/world-africa-15819797


A 4-fold increase in polio has been reported in Nigeria, with the
disease spreading to other countries, a World Health Organisation
official says.

Forty-three cases were reported in Nigeria this year [2011], compared
to 11 last year [2010], the official, Thomas Moran, said.

Curbing the polio virus in Nigeria is key to eradicating the crippling
disease in Africa, he said.

In 2003, northern Nigeria's Muslim leaders opposed vaccinations,
claiming they could cause infertility.

Nigeria is one of 4 countries in the world -- along with Pakistan,
India, and Afghanistan -- where polio is still a major health risk.

Mr Moran told the BBC the disease had also spread to neighbouring
Niger, Mali, and Ivory Coast.

"The success of polio eradication in Africa rests on Nigeria
interrupting the virus," he said.

Polio was affecting 8 northern Nigerian states -- 2 more than a few
months ago, the head of Nigeria's National Primary Healthcare
Development Agency (NPHDA), Dr Ado Muhammad, told the BBC.

Mr Moran said the Nigerian government had shown "strong leadership" in
the campaign to eradicate polio and the WHO had been carrying out
large scale vaccination programmes to prevent the disease from
spreading.

"The immunity profile of Nigerian children is far better [now], which
limits the risk of international spread of the virus," Mr Moran said.
He also stressed that the number of children affected remained low.

"You can call it a 4-fold increase but it is still very low
transmission in a country as large as Nigeria with almost 50 [million]
children under 5 [years old]," he said.

At the Commonwealth summit last month [October 2011], the leaders of
Nigeria, Canada, the UK, and Australia pledged millions of dollars
towards the global effort to eradicate polio.

In 2003, the northern Nigerian state of Kano backed Muslim religious
leaders in opposing an immunisation programme, claiming it was a
Western plot to make people infertile. Health experts say this led to
many people becoming infected by polio.

The clerics and the state government later dropped their opposition to
the immunisation programme.

In 2007, there was a rare outbreak of a vaccine-derived form of polio
in northern Nigeria.

It affected 69 children who had been vaccinated.

