[The newswire discussion in [1] on the polio situation in Nigeria is a
deja vu for discussions back in 2004 through 2006 when Nigeria was the
leading exporter of wild poliovirus to other countries in Africa, and
subsequently outside of Africa (Indonesia) (see prior ProMED-mail
posts listed below). It is sad that the situation continues to the
present, with continued transmission of the WPV (types 1 and 3) and
re-seeding of countries that had interrupted WPV transmission for 2 or
more years.

Of note, the newswire on the situation in Nigeria mentions there had
been a significant outbreak of polio due to infection with circulating
vaccine derived poliovirus (cVDPV) in Nigeria in 2007 involving 69
children. In fact, cVDPV associated polio continues to be a problem in
Nigeria, with 71 cases reported in 2007, 66 cases reported in 2008,
154 cases reported in 2009, 27 cases reported in 2010, and 20 cases
reported in 2011 as of 15 Nov 2011
(http://www.polioeradication.org/Dataandmonitoring/Poliothisweek/Circulatingvaccinederivedpoliovirus.aspx).
As mentioned in prior ProMED-mail posts on reported cases of polio
associated with cVDPV, these cases tend to occur in areas with
inadequate vaccination coverages, further supporting the observation
that vaccination coverages in Nigeria are suboptimal. The continued
circulation of VDPVs contributes to rumors that the vaccine is
damaging children, continuing the cycle of vaccine refusal.

In terms of absolute numbers of cases of polio, the countries with the
most reported cases in decreasing order are: Pakistan (145 cases),
Chad (117), DR Congo (86), Afghanistan (53), Nigeria (42) and Cote
d'Ivoire (36). Pakistan has reported almost 1/3 of all cases reported
in 2011, with transmission documented throughout the country. (For
more details on the types of wild poliovirus identified in each
country, please go to the Polio Eradication Initiative weekly update
webpage at
http://www.polioeradication.org/Dataandmonitoring/Poliothisweek.aspx.

For a map showing locations of all WPV associated paralytic polio
cases reported worldwide as of 16 Nov 2011, see the map at
http://www.polioeradication.org/Dataandmonitoring/Poliothisweek/Poliocasesworldwide.aspx.
- Mod.MPP]
